This doesn't do a lot for me. It's fairly short, the characters don't get much time to develop, and the events depicted are pretty straightforward. The even consistency of everything prevents the buildup of tension, and the bit that accumulates just before the security theater cutoff is immediately defused. Ideally, I would really want to see more at risk at some point throughout, either in terms of information security, the character's personal safety, or something else. As is, the article's calm doesn't feel tenuous at any point.





